omination of incumbent MPs on voters' loyalty, and in doing so, demonstrates how party organization greatly affects electoral stability. Including case studies from Bulgaria, Czech Republic, Hungary, Poland, Romania, and Slovakia this book will be of interest to students and scholars of comparative politics, party politics, democratization, elections, and Central and Eastern European politics"--cProvided by publisher.  a43 0aPolitical partieszEurope, Central. 0aPolitical partieszEurope, Eastern. 0aParty affiliationzEurope, Central. 0aParty affiliationzEurope, Eastern. 0aVoting researchzEurope, Central. 0aVoting researchzEurope, Eastern. 0aElectionszEurope, Central. 0aElectionszEurope, Eastern. 0aEurope, CentralxPolitics and governmenty1989- 0aEurope, EasternxPolitics and governmenty1989- 0aRoutledge research in comparative politics ;v61.  aJN 96 A979 G44 2015c1hUAHS-Bi0162035206133  aJN 96 A979 G44 2015wLCc1i0162035206133lON_SHELFmUAHSSp$150.00rYsYtBOOKu1/6/201501ahttp://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/nb2009020696bhttp://viaf.org/viaf/3.07145911115e+20